Statistical Testing in Python
We can use the chisquare method of scipy.stats. When the
expected frequencies are equal, they can be omitted:
>>> from scipy.stats import chisquare
>>> chisquare([16, 18, 16, 14, 12, 12])
(2.0, 0.84914503608460956)
The 2nd result is the p-value, the signicance of the
deviation.
Simple statistics with PySpark
The previous Python statistics work ne for small data, but
we need to do better for Big Data.
We can put the data into an RDD, accessed through Spark.
>>> from linalg import Vectors
>>> rdd = sc.parallelize([Vectors.dense([2, 0, 0, -2]),
... Vectors.dense([4, 5, 0, 3]),
... Vectors.dense([6, 7, 0, 8])])
>>> cStats = Statistics.colStats(rdd)
>>> cStats.mean()
array([ 4., 4., 0., 3.])
>>> cStats.variance()
array([ 4., 13., 0., 25.])
